10 Mental Traps That Quietly Control Your Thinking  Our brain is not a tool for truth, it is a tool for survival. It doesn‚Äôt look for what‚Äôs right, it looks for what‚Äôs fast.  Every decision passes through hidden filters. They save energy but distort perception.  That‚Äôs why smart people make stupid mistakes. Not because they‚Äôre stupid, but because they‚Äôre human.  Here are 10 traps we all fall into:  1. Confirmation Bias ‚Ü≥ you only notice what confirms your beliefs.  2. Dunning‚ÄìKruger Effect ‚Ü≥ the less you know, the more confident you feel.  3. Sunk Cost Fallacy ‚Ü≥ you keep going simply because you‚Äôve already invested.  4. Negativity Bias ‚Ü≥ one bad event outweighs ten good ones.  5. Anchoring Bias ‚Ü≥ the first number or idea distorts everything that follows.  6. Halo Effect ‚Ü≥ charisma makes you believe in competence.  7. Authority Bias ‚Ü≥ you trust confidence, not accuracy.  8. Availability Heuristic ‚Ü≥ what‚Äôs easier to recall feels more true.  9. Groupthink ‚Ü≥ you stay silent to fit in.  10. Survivorship Bias ‚Ü≥ you study the winners and forget the ones who didn‚Äôt make it.  Our brain was built to survive, not to understand. Awareness is the only way out of this game.  Below is the infographic with a deeper breakdown of each trap, with examples and simple ways to spot and neutralize them.  üí¨ Which of these traps do you fall for most often?  ‚Äî @natan_mohart

üö®TUTORIAL ALERT!!!üö® Comment "GEM" for the Project File Link.  Tutorial we all have been waiting for!!!!  Step-By-Step Guide on:  How to create a 3D Anime Crystal in Adobe After Effects?  Step 1- Create a crystal shape using the pen tool. Draw a mask over it, turn on the 3D switch, and add stroke effect on it.  Step 2- By rotating the shapes inwards, create a 3D crystal-like shape; the points of each shape should be connected. Make a similar crystal but with a fill in another comp.  Step 3- Duplicate both stroke and fill comps and link both of them to a Null object, and flip it to form a whole crystal.  Step 4- Add 2 point lights to give some depth and a crystal-like hue.  Step 5- Add roughen edges to the stroke comp and change the blending mode to overlay.  Step 6- Add a Deep glow to the crystal using an adjustment layer.   Step 7- Add Twinkly sparkles to the crystal to give it a shinier look.  The Anime Crystal Is Ready!!!!  Try creating by yourself! Don't forget to tag me!! üö®TUTORIAL ALERT!!!üö® Comment "GEM" for the Project File Link.  Tutorial we all have been waiting for!!!!  Step-By-Step Guide on:  How to create a 3D Anime Crystal in Adobe After Effects?  Step 1- Create a crystal shape using the pen tool. Draw a mask over it, turn on the 3D switch, and add stroke effect on it.  Step 2- By rotating the shapes inwards, create a 3D crystal-like shape; the points of each shape should be connected. Make a similar crystal but with a fill in another comp.  Step 3- Duplicate both stroke and fill comps and link both of them to a Null object, and flip it to form a whole crystal.  Step 4- Add 2 point lights to give some depth and a crystal-like hue.  Step 5- Add roughen edges to the stroke comp and change the blending mode to overlay.  Step 6- Add a Deep glow to the crystal using an adjustment layer.   Step 7- Add Twinkly sparkles to the crystal to give it a shinier look.  The Anime Crystal Is Ready!!!!  Try creating by yourself! Don't forget to tag me!! 10 Mental Traps That Quietly Control Your Thinking  Our brain is not a tool for truth, it is a tool for survival. It doesn‚Äôt look for what‚Äôs right, it looks for what‚Äôs fast.  Every decision passes through hidden filters. They save energy but distort perception.  That‚Äôs why smart people make stupid mistakes. Not because they‚Äôre stupid, but because they‚Äôre human.  Here are 10 traps we all fall into:  1. Confirmation Bias ‚Ü≥ you only notice what confirms your beliefs.  2. Dunning‚ÄìKruger Effect ‚Ü≥ the less you know, the more confident you feel.  3. Sunk Cost Fallacy ‚Ü≥ you keep going simply because you‚Äôve already invested.  4. Negativity Bias ‚Ü≥ one bad event outweighs ten good ones.  5. Anchoring Bias ‚Ü≥ the first number or idea distorts everything that follows.  6. Halo Effect ‚Ü≥ charisma makes you believe in competence.  7. Authority Bias ‚Ü≥ you trust confidence, not accuracy.  8. Availability Heuristic ‚Ü≥ what‚Äôs easier to recall feels more true.  9. Groupthink ‚Ü≥ you stay silent to fit in.  10. Survivorship Bias ‚Ü≥ you study the winners and forget the ones who didn‚Äôt make it.  Our brain was built to survive, not to understand. Awareness is the only way out of this game.  Below is the infographic with a deeper breakdown of each trap, with examples and simple ways to spot and neutralize them.  üí¨ Which of these traps do you fall for most often?  ‚Äî @natan_mohart
